 As previously noted, see note 14 supra, the methodology employed by Dr. McClave is widely accepted for calculating 
overcharges in antitrust litigation. See also In re Blood Reagents Antitrust Litigation, 283 F.R.D. 222, 241 (E.D. Pa. (2012); 
 [**110] Linerboard, 305 F.3d at 153-55; McDonough, 638 F.Supp.2d at 490 n. 19.

 Rule 23(b)(3) lists the following factors: (A) HN25[
] the interest of members of the class in individually controlling the prosecution or defense of separate actions; 
(B) the extent and nature of any litigation concerning the controversy already commenced by or against members of the 
class; (c) the desirability or undesirability of concentrating the litigation of the claims in the particular forum; (D) the 
difficulties likely to be encountered in the management of a class action. Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(b)(3).

